! Ways cell gene expression can be controlled or disrupted!

Transcriptional regulation: 
- Adding {{c1::methyl groups}} on the {{c1::sequence}} a transcription factor needs to bind to will {{c1::decrease}} transcription of a gene and it's expression.  
- Mutations or methylation of introns can cause {{c1::improper splicing}} (removal of interons), causing {{c1::exons}} to be left out or junk introns being left in the final {{c1::mRNA transcript}}. This messes up the proteins shape causing it to be {{c1::ubiquitied}} (targeted for destruction) by the {{c1::unfolded protein response}} (UPR). 

Translational Regulation 
- Micro RNAs (miRNA) can {{c1::bind to an mRNA transcript}} causing it to jam when trying to be {{c1::translated by the ribosome}}. 

Histone regulation 
- {{c1::HATS}} Open up histones {{c1::(increasing transcriptional access and gene expression)}} by adding negative acytal groups. 
- {{c1::DACS}} deacetylate histones {{c1::(decrease transcriptional access and gene expression)}} allowing the now more positive histones hold negative DNA more tightly.
* Differentiate the means in which gene expression can be controlled or disrupted. (1 Q on exam involving methylation or histones)

Describe the role glucose as a fuel source in different tissues. 

These cells use glucose as their primary energy source: {{c1::Neurons}} (brain tissue), {{c1::RBCs}} (contain no mitochondria).

Normal blood glucose levels peak {{c1::1}} hour after a meal then should be {{c1::80-100}} mg/dl {{c1::2}} hours after eating... Mercedies!
* Describe the role glucose as a fuel source in different tissues.

Fed State 
  • Digestive tract breaks down carbs into {{c1::monosaccharides}} (simple sugars like glucose) and proteins into amino acids which go to {{c1::liver, brain, and muscles}}.  
  • Liver starts creating these 3 important things: 
    • 1. {{c1::Glycogen}} in a process called glycogenosis using {{c1::monosaccharides}} from digestion. 
    • 2. {{c1::Triacylglycerols}} in the process of Triacylglycerol Synthesis using {{c1::monosaccharides}} from digestion. 
    • 3. {{c1::Albumin}} using Amino acids from digestion.  
  • Adipose tissue stores fat droplets that it creates from triacylglycerols sent through the blood on chylomicrons (cholesterol balls) from the intestinal epithelial cells. 
Fasting State 
  • Liver starts {{c1::glycogenolysis}} to break down glycogen and breaks down {{c1::fatty acids}} into ketone bodes. 
  • Adipose tissue begins {{c1::lipolysis}} which oxidizes triacylglycerols to produce either {{c1::acetyl-coA}} for the Krebs aka {{c1::tricarboxylic acid}} (TCA) cycle. Can also oxidizes triacylglycerols into {{c1::ketone}} bodies.
* Compare and contrast metabolic processes during the fed and fasting states.

Compare and contrast the histologic layers of the GI tract and the important neurological plexi:
1. Outer {{c1::serosa}} (faces blood)
2. {{c1::Muscularis}} externa
  • Outer longitudinal and inner circular muscle layers {{c1::motilty}}

  • Lies between circular and longitudinal muscle layers

  • Consists of epithelium, lamina propria (collagen, glands, capillaries), and muscularis mucosa (inner smooth muscle) {{c1::absorption & secretions}}

Know the major sphincters in the GI tract and how they and peristalsis promote unidirectional movement of chyme. 
  • Sphincters are {{c1::circular muscle rings}} with resting tone that normally remain {{c1::constricted/closed}} until signaled to {{c1::relax}}.
  • They regulate {{c1::uni-directional}} movement of chyme through the GI tract
  • *Unless emessis ({{c1::reverse}} direction)*
  1. Upper esophageal sphincter ({{c1::pharynx}} and {{c1::esophagus}})
  2. Lower esophageal sphincter ({{c1::esophagus}} and {{c1::stomach}})
  3. Pyloric sphincter ({{c1::stomach}} and {{c1::small}} bowel)- Relax to allow stomach content into Duodenum
  4. Ileocecal sphincter ({{c1::small}} bowel and {{c1::colon}})
  5. Internal anal sphincter ({{c1::rectum}} and {{c1::anus}}, {{c1::involuntary}} controlled smooth muscle)
  6. External anal sphincter ({{c1::rectum}} and {{c1::anus}}, {{c1::voluntary}} controlled skeletal muscle)
*Know the major sphincters in the GI tract and how they and peristalsis promote unidirectional movement of chyme.

Describe the three phases of swallowing and be able to apply this knowledge to potential medical problems including but not limited to aspiration, stroke, achalasia, GERD:
Oral Phase:
  • {{c1::Tongue}} pushes bolus into {{c1::pharynx}}
  • Stretch receptor signal to {{c1::medulla}} and initiate {{c1::swallowing}} reflex
potential medical problems :
  • {{c1::Losing muscle tone- stroke/ neurological defects}}
Pharyngeal Phase
  • {{c1::Soft}} palate raised, {{c1::epiglottis}} covers airway, {{c1::UES}} relaxes
  • {{c1::Peristaltic}} wave in {{c1::pharynx}}
potential medical problems :
  • {{c1::Aspiration- non control of epiglottis, stroke/ Central neurological problem}}
Esophageal Phase
  • {{c1::Peristaltic}} wave moves bolus through esophagus
  • {{c1::LES}} relaxes
 potential medical problems:
  • {{c1::Achalasia}}- esophageal stenosis
  • GERD- Pressure in stomach is {{c1::greater}} than pressure of {{c1::LES}}
  • {{c1::Uncoordinated}} Peristaltic waves -Central neurological problem

  • {{c1::Secretin}} and {{c1::GIP}} decrease contractions
*Describe the key components regulating GI motility

Parasympathetic

  • Peptidergic: Substance {{c1::P}}; {{c1::vasoactive intestinal peptide}} (VIP) 
{{c1::Excitatory}} fibers (can also be inhibitory, mediating relaxation of the lower esophageal sphincter (LES) and stomach during swallowing)

{{c1::Enhances}} activity of enteric system and overall GI activity (muscle contractions, motility, secretion, and hormonal release)

Understand the process of smooth muscle contraction and how it differs from skeletal and cardiac muscle contraction:
  • Basically the same as skeletal except Actin-myosin NOT organized into {{c1::sarcomeres}}:
  • Ca+2 binds {{c1::calmodulin}} 
  • Facilitates the myosin-actin cross bridging by activating myosin-light chain kinase to phosphorylate myosin light chain 
  • Smooth muscle: Increases myosin ATPase activity which {{c1::enhances}} conversion of {{c1::ATP-Myosin}} (unbound to actin) to {{c1::ADP-Myosin}} (actin bound)  rate-limiting step in smooth muscle contraction
  • Skeletal muscle primary rate-limiting step is {{c1::actin binding site availability}}
*Understand the process of smooth muscle contraction and how it differs from skeletal and cardiac muscle contraction

Compare and contrast how GI smooth muscle contraction and depolarization/action potentials differ from skeletal muscle contraction and action potentials:

Threshold is reached:
  • {{c1::Many}} action potentials fire and {{c1::cumulate}} into {{c1::a certain strength}} of smooth muscle contraction.
  • Contrasts with skeletal muscle, where {{c1::each}} action potential results in {{c1::a certain strength}} contraction
*Compare and contrast how GI smooth muscle contraction and depolarization/action potentials differ from skeletal muscle contraction and action potentials

Recognize classic presentation of and explain the pathophysiology of hiatal hernia and achalasia:
Hiatal Hernia:
S/S: heartburn, difficulty keeping food down, worsening {{c1::breathing}}, "{{c1::Gurgling}}" sounds @ auscultations of LL lung
(confirm with xRay: stomach over top of diaphragm, no fever, no cough.)
Achalasia:
S/S: Difficulty {{c1::swallowing}}, {{c1::chest}} pain, vomiting, heartburn
Vomit up undigested bolus due to failure of {{c1::lower esophageal spinctor}} ({{c1::LES}})
* Recognize classic presentation of and explain the pathophysiology of hiatal hernia and achalasia

What is ileus?
{{c1::Inability}} of the intestine ({{c1::bowel}}) to {{c1::contract}} normally and move waste out of the body

Of note: clinicians usually refer to the small intestines as {{c1::bowel}} and the large intestines as {{c1::colon}}.

What is the most likey Diagonosis?
{{c1::Peptic Ulcer}}
  • Symptoms: Abdominal pain/bloating; nausea, hemetemesis (vomiting blood); waterbrash (rush of saliva after an episode of regurgitation to dilute the acid in esophagus); melena (tarry, foul-smelling feces due to oxidized iron from Hb); gastric or duodenal perforation.
  • Treatments: Antacids, H2 antagonists.
 With H. pylori infection, the most effective treatments are combinations of 2 antibiotics (e.g. Clarithromycin, Amoxicillin, Tetracycline, Metronidazole) and 1 proton pump inhibitor (PPI), sometimes together with a bismuth compound.
  • 80% of {{c1::ulcers}} are associated with Helicobacter pylori, a spiral-shaped bacterium that lives in acidic stomach environment

and 3. {{c5::constitutive activity}}-{{c7::the basic level of physiologic response in the absence of agonist}}

An agonist is a {{c1::drug that binds to a receptor and produces an effect.}} A full agonist produces {{c2::maximal effect,}} a partial agonist produces {{c3::submaximal effect,}} and an inverse agonist produces a {{c4::negative effect}} by {{c5::inhibiting constitutive activity}}
